04646nam a22006495i 9780804795203DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047952037 a10.1515/97808047952032doi  a(DE-B1597)563811  a(OCoLC)1198931205  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS119.7 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a394/.408992741 aSorek, Tamir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPalestinian Commemoration in Israel :bCalendars, Monuments, and Martyrs /cTamir Sorek. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. COMMEMORATION UNDER BRITISH RULE -- t2. THE KAFR QASIM MASSACRE AND LAND DAY -- t3. THE POLITICAL CALENDAR IN THE TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY -- t4. MEMORIALS FOR MARTYRS, I (1976-1983) -- t5. MEMORIALS FOR MARTYRS, II (1998-2013) -- t6. ON THE MARGINS OF COMMEMORATION -- t7. DISCIPLINING PALESTINIAN MEMORY -- t8. THE STRUGGLE OVER THE NEXT GENERATION -- t9. POLITICAL SUMMER CAMPS -- t10. THE QUEST FOR VICTORY -- t11. LATENT NOSTALGIA FOR YITZHAK RABIN -- tCONCLUSION -- tAPPENDIX -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCollective memory transforms historical events into political myths. In this book, Tamir Sorek considers the development of collective memory and national commemoration among the Palestinian citizens of Israel. He charts the popular politicization of four key events-the Nakba, the 1956 Kafr Qasim Massacre, the 1976 Land Day, and the October 2000 killing of twelve Palestinian citizens in Israel-and investigates a range of commemorative sites, including memorial rallies, monuments, poetry, the education system, political summer camps, and individual historical remembrance. These sites have become battlefields between diverse social forces and actors-including Arab political parties, the Israeli government and security services, local authorities, grassroots organizations, journalists, and artists-over representations of the past. Palestinian commemorations are uniquely tied to Palestinian encounters with the Israeli state apparatus, with Jewish Israeli citizens of Israel, and by their position as Israeli citizens themselves. Reflecting longstanding tensions between Palestinian citizens and the Israeli state, as well as growing pressures across Palestinian societies within and beyond Israel, these moments of commemoration distinguish Palestinian citizens not only from Jewish citizens, but from Palestinians elsewhere. Ultimately, Sorek shows that Palestinian citizens have developed commemorations and a collective memory that offers both moments of protest and points of dialogue, that is both cautious and circuitous.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxAnniversaries, etc. 0aCollective memoryzIsrael. 0aMemorializationzIsrael. 0aMemorialszIsrael. 0aMuslim martyrszIsraelxAnniversaries, etc. 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxAnniversaries, etc. 4aIsrael. 4aPalestinians. 4acitizenship. 4acollective memory. 4aethnic conflicts. 4aminorities. 4anational identity. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479520340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804795203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804795203.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-d